{"key":"processedPost-20000812","value":{"id":20000812,"first":19996474,"last":20003456,"when":1400330130,"utime":"05/17/14 03:35 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />This has been a heated debate for years, most labs store their plates upside down, while most old school myco dudes (aka RR) absolutely disagree with this storage method. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />No, most labs do not store petri dishes upside down.&nbsp; In fact, I know of absolutely zero mycology labs which would use such a poor procedure.&nbsp; Local labs which test water samples and the like do so because they only keep the cultures for a few days.&nbsp; If they kept them upside down in the refrigerator for a week, all the moisture would have drained out to the lid.<br /><br />To the original poster, condensation is caused by temperature differential.&nbsp; Simply wrap up or otherwise insulate the dishes for storage in an insulated lunch box or similar and always store cultures right side up.<br />RR","title":"Re: How to prevent moisture in petri disc","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}